{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"885b5a06-0445-417d-93aa-ea658d50574c","content":"I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files during evaluation is expensive — evaluation runs frequently (IDE reload, restore, every build). **Fix:** Move this to a target that runs at build time, or use a `ReadLinesFromFile` task.\n\n### 2. Expensive Recursive Glob (line 9, `EvalHeavy.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**. If folders like `node_modules`, `.git`, or large artifact directories exist, this becomes very slow. **Fix:** Narrow the glob (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or add heavy directories to `$(DefaultItemExcludes)`.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (3 levels deep)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. At 3 levels this is manageable, but it's a pattern that degrades as depth grows. **Fix:** Flatten into fewer files where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Highest impact fix:** Remove the `File::ReadAllText` property function — file I/O during evaluation is the most costly pattern here.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b65b958e-7cbb-4242-9b7d-6ba507d69da2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe project has several evaluation performance anti-patterns:\n\n1. **File I/O during evaluation** (line 13): `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` — This is a property function that performs file I/O during project evaluation. This is expensive because evaluation happens frequently (IDE, restore, build).\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** (line 9): `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` — This is a recursive glob that walks the entire directory tree. If the project directory contains large folders (like `node_modules`, `.git`, etc.), this can be very slow. It should be constrained or items should be added to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n   \n3. **Deep import chain** (lines 6, level1→level2→level3): There's a 3-level deep import chain where each file imports the next. While not severe yet, this pattern compounds evaluation time and could become problematic as the chain grows deeper.","outputTokens":651,"requestId":"7803:204131:874EF19:95B6CD1:69EAC4CD"},"id":"82fe8898-9728-4fb1-b2f6-9f329f1b1796","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:18:20.088Z","parentId":"680bb837-b45e-46ad-8567-c097ee8a1dfe"}
